0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang2057\fs18 Additionally if a pointer to an internal routine in the EASYMENU generated menu}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li19\fi0\ri0\sb5\sa0\sl-221\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf0\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang2057\fs18 definition is zero, then EM_SETUP will replace it by it's own routine. If the pointer}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li24\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-221\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf0\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang2057\fs18 is not zero, then EM_SETUP assumes that you have an own routine there and}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li10\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-221\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf0\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang2057\fs18 sets this routine.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li19\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-221\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf0\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang2057\fs18 More detailed information about the handling of action routines is given in 4.5.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li14\fi0\ri0\sb226\sa0\sl-216\slmult0\tx307 \f1\fs20{\i0\b\cf0\charscalex100\expndtw-3\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang2057\fs18 4.2\expndtw0 {\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }Register A5 and A6}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb5\sa0\sl-216\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf0\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang2057\fs18 Registers A5 and A6 are in no way affected by the EASYMENU Library Routines. Thus e.g. they can be used to point to private data areas accessible from within the internal setup or action routines.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li10\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-216\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf0\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang2057\fs18 For C this principally means, that local parameters of the calling routine would be accessible from within internal routines.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5\fi0\ri0\sb230\sa0\tx307 \f1\fs20{\i0\b\cf0\charscalex100\expndtw-3\dn0\f1\cchs0\lang2057\fs18 4.3\expndtw0 {\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }Address Pointers (C only)}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li19\fi0\ri0\sb5\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf0\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f